      <hedline>
        <hl1>What Is Marriage?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Christine Ross letter on Jane Smiley's Sept 12 Op-Ed; says that when feminists and others began deconstructing marriage, they lost sight of its fundamental meaning (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''There They Go, Bad-Mouthing Divorce Again,'' by Jane Smiley (Op-Ed, Sept. 12):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''There They Go, Bad-Mouthing Divorce Again,'' by Jane Smiley (Op-Ed, Sept. 12):</p>
        <p>Ms. Smiley says: ''Marrying with the overriding goal of being happy for all your adult life with a single other . . . is a new experiment. Divorce is its corollary.'' Yet decisions like divorce should be judged by criteria that extend beyond a person's own motivations. Divorce has a decisive impact on children and others.</p>
        <p>Marriage for most people means the creation of a self-transcending reality in which individual happiness can be achieved. Regardless of one's religious beliefs or lack thereof, it is this paradox that attracts people to marriage.</p>
        <p>When feminists and others began deconstructing marriage, they lost sight of its fundamental meaning.</p>
        <p>CHRISTINE ROSS  Reston, Va., Sept. 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
